[UTCTime "23:54:54"]

{ Another important aspect in positional chess is the golden strategy, advocated by GM Jacob Aagaard back in the 2010s. As the concept is spoken in foreign chessy language, I'll simplify it for you:
1. What is my worst placed piece?
2. What are the weaknesses?
3. What is my opponent's plan? }
 *


[Event "Mastering Positional Chess!: What is my worst placed piece?♔🤔"]
[Date "2026.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Mastering Positional Chess!"]
[ChapterName "What is my worst placed piece?♔🤔"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/l0AuLlTT/jwyARe4m"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/RushConnectedPawns"]
[FEN "4r1k1/5p1p/np3bp1/1b2p3/p3P2P/P1R2NPB/1BP2P2/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2026.06.03"]
[UTCTime "23:54:54"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Let's evaluate this position and ask the 3 questions.
1. What is the worst placed piece? (The bishop on h3, obviously)
2. What are the weaknesses? (Arguably, e5 and c2)
3. What is my opponent's plan? (Probably Nc5 attacking e4)

Now, with these hints, find the best move for white! } { [%csl Rc2,Re5,Rh3,Be4][%cal Ba6c5,Bc5e4] }
1. Bf1! { Brilliant! White improves his worst placed piece and also trades off black's best piece. } *


